> /OOC:  The events detailed in this chronicle happened on the eve just before the events related in the thread &quot;Whispering Shadows&quot;. <br>
<br>
<br>
Sabratha ran all the way from the commonlands to Neriak as fast as her little legs would carry her.  The Pale Man Rohwin had really upset her, and she wasn't even sure why.  He had been pressing her for answers concerning her parentage.  NO one had ever asked her outright about these things and well... she was just tired.  The Dreaming had been particularly intense last night.  The One who ran the castle had been in it, but this time it was she he was torturing and not Daiunus.  This was the first time she had dreamed she was in actual contact with the inhabitants of the castle, and she had not felt well all day, as a result.  <br>
Rohwin had upset her so much, she had lost control of her magical energies, and that had not happened for a very long time.  She had to find her mother.<br>
Sabratha tore into the flat calling for her, but she wasn't home.  She raced on to the Grange, out of breath, still dangerously fluctuating with wild magical energy.  <br>
She had not been to the Grange in a while, and very few people were there now, mostly servants.  There was a sickly sweet odor lingering here... it smelled like the castle... it smelled overwhelmingly of blood.<br>
Those congregated in the main hall stared wildly at her, fearfully even.<br>
&quot;Where is my mother?&quot;  The child glanced anxiously about for someone to help her.  Something was happening to her, something she did not understand.  Her hair blew about, fueled by the still unsettled magics in her.<br>
No one answered, perhaps no one knew.<br>
&quot;WHERE is my mother?  Where is Payle?&quot;  She was practically screaming now.  A lesser child would have wept, but Sabratha had never given in to tears.<br>
From a side room, the young enchantress Kehle entered, perhaps drawn by the commotion.  Only a few years older than Sabratha, she approached to try and calm the child.  She stopped short when she realized, how dangerously out of control the child was at them moment.<br>
&quot;Calm down, little one... your mother is not here.  She is away on a task for now.  Perhaps, I can help you.&quot;  She smiled, hoping to comfort the young one.<br>
Sabratha shook with frustration and confusion.<br>
&quot;She is ALWAYS away,&quot; she screamed at anyone unlucky enough to still be in the room.  And with that, she turned and fled the Grange, leaving a trail of fiery sparks in her wake.<br>
The young one Kehle remained calm.  &quot;Someone had better go fetch Payle&quot;, she said and indicated to one of the servants.<br>
<br>
Sabratha kept running through Third Gate until she came to the underground river.  Finally having spent her emotional havoc, she dropped herself onto a large rock by the water.  This was her favorite secret spot.  The rock walls formed a small grotto, and she liked to sit here and watch the fish swim.  <br>
A terrible feeling of reckoning overwhelmed the tiny, confused child right before she noticed a large, organic object lodged on the rocks, its long white, soggy locks still submerged.<br>
Zombie-like, she moved to fetch it out of the water, pulling it up by its hair.  She turned the head over to face her.  Shock would have caused her to drop it, were it not for the fact that she was strangely compelled to hang onto it.<br>
Sabratha stared into the inanimate eyes of the One who ran the castle.  A unexpected sense of calm enveloped her; all traces of her former confusion fled.  Knowing her mother would not approve of her new trophy, she carefully concealed it by rolling it in her satin cloak, and began to make her way back home.<br>
