<br>
<br>
Payle had been in the Forest when she felt the vengeful blood red orb ascend past the horizon.  She froze for a few moments, confused.  She quickly counted days in her mind... it couldn't be.  But yet somehow, it was.  It seemed that with all the tribulations within her family as of late, she had lost track of the days, weeks even.  And it was with a very sick heart that she realized the moon that the people to whom she had been born called the Blood Moon, was making its annual ascent into the evening sky.  <br>
But something far more dreadful than the usual emotions she felt on this night were gripping her now.  She was assaulted by a very real terror, and somehow instinctively she knew her daughter Sabratha was in terrible danger.  She did not even take the time to gather her herb hunting supplies.  She called on the spirit of the dark wolf, the wolf as hunter, to aid her, and fled toward the city at the fastest speed possible.  <br>
She bounded the steps up to their flat two at a time, calling for Sabratha.  She found her child lying upon her bed, fully clothed, her eyes open wide and staring at the ceiling.  The room was unbearably warm.  Payle drew near to her.  The heat seemed to be emanating from her.  She touched her hand to Sabratha's forehead, and it practically burned her.  <br>
&quot;Sabratha, you are ill... what has happened to you?&quot;  Payle tried to remain calm.<br>
&quot;Mother?&quot;  Sabratha's voice was barely a whisper.  Her eyes remained focused on the ceiling.  &quot;What's wrong with me?&quot;<br>
&quot;Nothing Sab,&quot; she tried to make her voice sound believable.  She knew in her heart that the time had come, and what terrible timing it was.  &quot;Just tell me what you can.&quot;<br>
&quot;I... I was in the commonlands.  That man Rohwin...&quot;  Sabratha's voice trailed off, a renewed surge of heat poured from her tiny body.  <br>
Payle bit back the swell of anger that threatened to overtake her senses.  &quot;Rohwin?  What of him?&quot;<br>
She listened through clenched teeth as Sabratha explained the exchange the two had had earlier in the day, and how she had lost control of her magical energy destroying a stray kitten unlucky enough to chance near her.  The terrible heat of the room fluctuated with her emotions, as she spoke.  <br>
&quot;What then, Sab?&quot;  <br>
&quot;I... I don't remember exactly... I ended up here.&quot;  A spike of heat nearly sent Payle from the room.  <br>
&quot;Make me some tea please Mother, with Feverfew.&quot;<br>
Payle blinked slowly.  &quot;Of course, Sab.&quot;<br>
She felt a terrible pang of guilt, realizing her daughter had been learning the art of herb lore and it had not come from her.  Gambel had been teaching her, she supposed.<br>
Payle went to make the tea, feeling as helpless as a mother ever had.  Moreso, perhaps, because she could feel the restless spirits around them, throughout the city, and she wasn't sure she had the power to protect those dear to her.  She could feel that awful moon out there, waiting for its chance.  Tonight, it was coming for Sabratha, but it would have a terrible fight for that prize.<br>
Payle helped Sabratha sip some of the tea.  She had added some Valerian to help her sleep.  Then she bagan to pray intensely to Innoruuk.  She called forth every ward and protection on them and thier flat that she knew, and summoned every guardian spirit that she could control.  By the time Sabratha was slipping into a restless slumber, their flat was as fortified as any castle.  <br>
<br>
That was when the screams began to reverberate throughout the city.<br>
